## Overall Trend in Pedestrian Collisions

In @fig-ped-by-year-all-days we see that the number of pedestrian collisions per year has been steadily decreasing since 2015.



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Total pedestrian collisions per year](analysis_files/figure-html/fig-ped-by-year-all-days-1.png){#fig-ped-by-year-all-days width=672}
:::
:::



## Pedestrian Collisions by Type of Traffic Control at Collision Location

In @fig-traffic-control-all-ped-collisions we see that just over half (129/231 or 56%) of all pedestrian collisions occurred at <span style="color: #551A8B; font-weight: bold;">locations with some type of traffic control in place</span>.



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Total pedestrian collisions by traffic control type](analysis_files/figure-html/fig-traffic-control-all-ped-collisions-1.png){#fig-traffic-control-all-ped-collisions width=672}
:::
:::



## Pedestrian Collisions Near Schools

@tbl-schped reports the schools that had at least one pedestrian collision within 250m. In total there were 28 pedestrian collisions within 250m of a school (one of these occurred within 250m of two schools, so the number of collisions below add to 29).



::: {#tbl-schped .cell tbl-cap='Schools with at least one pedestrian collision within 250m'}
::: {.cell-output-display}

